{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535651"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:58:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:58:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15493"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15493"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.69,0.18,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61703"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8184"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47149"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5394"},{"type":"tags","id":"11724"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19813"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61703"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting advice about hormone replacement therapy (HRT). She is interested in the relationship between HRT and breast cancer. You review a recent cohort study examining this association. The study found that among 1,000 HRT users, 45 developed breast cancer, while among 2,000 non-users, 30 developed breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the relative risk of breast cancer in HRT users compared to non-users?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["4.0","3.0","1.5","2.0","5.0"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of relative risk calculation in epidemiological studies. Relative risk (RR) is calculated by comparing the incidence of disease in exposed versus unexposed groups.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe data can be presented in a 2x2 table:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022 style=\u0022border-collapse:collapse;width:100%;\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EBreast Cancer\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ENo Breast Cancer\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ETotal\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EHRT Use\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E45\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E955\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E1000\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ENo HRT Use\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E30\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E1970\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E2000\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo calculate relative risk:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. Calculate risk in exposed group (HRT users):\u003Cbr /\u003E45/1000 = 0.045 or 4.5%\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. Calculate risk in unexposed group (non-HRT users):\u003Cbr /\u003E30/2000 = 0.015 or 1.5%\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. Calculate relative risk:\u003Cbr /\u003E0.045/0.015 = \u003Cstrong\u003E3.0\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1.5\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E2.0\u003C/strong\u003E are incorrect as they underestimate the relative risk. These might be confused with other epidemiological measures such as risk difference.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E4.0\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E5.0\u003C/strong\u003E are incorrect as they overestimate the relative risk. These might result from incorrect calculation methods or confusion with odds ratios.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor comparison, the odds ratio (OR) for this data would be:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOR = (45 \u00d7 1970) / (955 \u00d7 30) = 3.09\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Relative risk compares the probability of an outcome between exposed and unexposed groups.","Relative risk is calculated by dividing the risk in the exposed group by the risk in the unexposed group.","In epidemiological studies, relative risk greater than 1 indicates increased risk in the exposed group."],"references":["Cook A, Sheikh A. Descriptive statistics (Part 2): Interpreting study results. Prim Care Respir J. 2000 Mar;8(1):16\u20137"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47149"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15493"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47149"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T11:28:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-16T11:29:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8184"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61703"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"da